The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                               The City Diary
                An eight-ft iron rod fell off the fourth floor of a building under construction in New Town and pierced the lungs, diaphragm, liver and stomach of labourer Sukumar Mondol on Wednesday afternoon.   ondol, 45, was working on the second floor of the building when the accident occurred. Doctors at NRS Medical College and Hospital removed the rod after a four-and-a-half-hour surgery. The condition of Mondol, a resident of Hasnabad in North 24-Parganas, was critical. In a similar incident on January 14, doctors at Medical College and Hospital saved the life of 21-year-old Sheikh Rezak after a steel shaft pierced his chest and emerged through the back.    A six-year-old girl, Salma Khatun, was run over and killed by a truck in Rabindra Nagar, on the southern city fringes, on Wednesday. Police said the girl was playing on the road when she was dashed by the truck. A mob damaged the vehicle but the driver fled.    A 22-year-old man, who had suffered head injuries in an accident 10 days ago, died at Ruby General Hospital on Wednesday. Relatives of the victim, Uttam Mandal, lodged a police complaint accusing the hospital staff of medical negligence. They also complained of inflated bills. The hospital authorities denied the allegations. Police have started a probe. Mandal, of Laugachhia in North 24-Parganas, was flung off his motorcycle at Sarberia on January 25 as he tried to save a child who had come in this path, his father said.     Kalu Paswan, 55, a constable of Railway Protection Force (RPF), was run over by the Janashatabdi Express at 5.45am while he was crossing the tracks near Bamangachi in Howrah. The body lay on the tracks for nearly three hours before it was sent for post-mortem, local residents said.    A 45-year-old government employee, Subodh Chandra Mondal, was found hanging at his Mahestala home on Wednesday. Police said Mondal and his wife Aloka were childless. The body was sent for post-mortem. An unnatural death case has been started.    A taxi driver was booked and his vehicle impounded after it collided with the motorcycle of a sergeant, Santosh Sinha, at the DL Khan Road-AJC Bose Road crossing on Wednesday. Sinha was taken to SSKM Hospital and discharged after treatment.    Hamida Bibi, 21, of Prince Rahimuddin Lane near Tollygunge, suffered 70 per cent burns when her clothes caught fire after a bottle of kerosene fell near the stove while she was cooking. She was admitted to MR Bangur Hospital. Her three-year-old son, who was also in the room, escaped unhurt.            
